cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 65 mi WSW of St. Petersburg, Florida
cyclone.trajectory: moving north, then turning north-northeast across northern Florida and emerging into the western Atlantic just north of Jacksonville, before continuing northeast toward the coastal Carolinas
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: Big Bend coast of Florida (near or just south of Cedar Key)

weather_observation.watch_coast: North of the Suwannee River to Aucilla River, FL (Big Bend area)
weather_observation.warning_coast: Bonita Beach to Suwannee River, FL (west-central Gulf coast including Tampa Bay)
weather_observation.impacted_coast: West-central and northern Florida peninsula, Big Bend, and Atlantic coast from northeast Florida through the Carolinas
weather_observation.wind: Tropical-storm-force gusts (40–50 mph) possible Thursday as the center passes inland then offshore just north of the port.
weather_observation.storm_surge: Minor surge (generally <2 ft) possible along St. Johns River mouth and adjacent beaches, but values above 3 ft are not expected.
weather_observation.rainfall: 1–3 inches of heavy rainfall bands Thursday; localized totals could approach 4 inches but widespread amounts remain lower.
weather_observation.other_hazards: A brief tornado can’t be ruled out in outer rain-bands, and rough seas/rip currents will affect approaches to the port.
